======================================================================
PART 4: FREIMAN'S THEOREM CONNECTION
======================================================================

Freiman's theorem: If |S+S| <= K|S|, then S is contained in
a generalized arithmetic progression of dimension d <= d(K).

For Interval: S = {1,...,m}, so S+S = {2,...,2m}.
|S+S| = 2m-1 = p-2, and |S| = m, so K = (p-2)/m ≈ 2.
This is the SMALLEST possible doubling constant!

For Paley: S = QR(p). By Weil bound on character sums,
|S+S| >= p - O(√p), so K ≈ 2 as well, but S+S is DENSE.

  p=7: |S+S| Int=5, Pal=6
